# What Should Not Be Done in Phase 1

The following are explicitly out of scope for this phase.

---

## Do not start with Python orchestration

Do not try to make Python run the model in this phase.

That introduces unnecessary complexity:
- headless NetLogo setup
- path configuration
- Java issues
- CSV assumptions before the model is valid

---

## Do not rely on BehaviorSpace yet

BehaviorSpace should not be the first validator of the architecture.

The model must first be shown to work directly inside NetLogo.

---

## Do not skip raw data storage

Do not only keep a running count of wins and forget durations or outcomes.

The implementation needs raw per-run data for reliability and validation.

---

## Do not merge all logic into one monolithic `go`

That will create confusion and make later BehaviorSpace integration fragile.

---

## Do not silently change the definition of victory

The implementation must preserve and explicitly define how victory and defeat are determined.

This is a core modeling assumption.

---

# Cursor / LLM Implementation Guidance

If an LLM is being used to modify the NetLogo model, it must be instructed to perform a **surgical refactor**, not a rewrite.

The agent should be told:

1. preserve existing battle logic
2. move existing tick logic into `go-step`
3. add new experiment-level procedures
4. add convergence globals and reporters
5. add per-run data storage
6. avoid deleting current domain-specific logic unless absolutely necessary
7. maintain compatibility with later BehaviorSpace integration

The agent should not be allowed to simplify the model just to make the controller easier.

---

# Required End-State After Phase 1

Phase 1 is complete only when all of the following are true.

---

## Functional requirements

- The model can run one battle to completion
- The model can run many battles sequentially inside one adaptive experiment
- Each internal battle begins from a fresh simulation state
- Each internal battle produces a stored outcome and duration
- Statistics update after every completed battle
- The experiment stops when the convergence criterion is met
- The experiment also stops if the safety cap is hit

---

## Statistical requirements

- `p-hat` reflects actual British win rate from completed runs
- `moe` uses the correct formula
- convergence is based on the MOE threshold
- the run count used in MOE is the number of completed internal runs

---

## Validation requirements

- No obvious state leakage
- No broken battle mechanics
- No premature battle termination
- No premature convergence
- No inconsistent victory logic

---

# Transition to Phase 2

Only after this phase is fully working should the project move to BehaviorSpace.

BehaviorSpace in Phase 2 will treat:

- `setup` as experiment initialization
- `go` as one full adaptive convergence process
- reported metrics as final aggregated outputs for one scenario

But that only works if Phase 1 is done correctly.

---

# Final Summary

Phase 1 is the foundation of the entire workflow.

It must be built inside the NetLogo model because that is where:

- the simulation actually exists
- battle outcomes are generated
- termination logic is defined
- randomness is applied
- convergence statistics get their data
- BehaviorSpace later hooks in

This phase is not just “coding.” It is:

- architecture refactoring
- statistical instrumentation
- battle termination definition
- data recording design
- convergence validation

A correct Python script later can only analyze good data.

A correct BehaviorSpace setup later can only automate a good model.

Therefore:

> Phase 1 must make the NetLogo model itself statistically aware, convergence-aware, and experiment-ready before anything external is attempted.
